Definition 4.1 ${\bf 2SVect}_{cc}$ is the strict 2-category with objects, 1-morphisms and 2-morphisms defined by: • objects: the natural numbers $n\geq 0$. • 1-morphisms: given $n,m\geq 1$, a 1-morphism $n\longrightarrow m$ is a pair $({\bf R},s)$, where (i) ${\bf R}$ (the rank matrix) is an $m\times n$ matrix $(R_{ij})$ with entries in $\mathbb{N}$, and (ii) $s$ (the gauge) is a collection $\{(s_{1}({\bf a}),\ldots,s_{m}({\bf a}))\}_{{\bf a}\in\mathbb{N}^{n}}$ with $s_{i}({\bf a})$ an ${\bf R}({\bf a})_{i}\times{\bf R}({\bf a})_{i}$ invertible complex matrix if ${\bf R}({\bf a})_{i}\neq 0$ and $s_{i}({\bf a})=1$ otherwise, and satisfying the following normalization condition: for all $i=1,\ldots,m$ and $j=1,\ldots,n$, it is $s_{i}({\bf e}_{j})=Id_{R_{ij}}$ whenever $R_{ij}={\bf R}({\bf e}_{j})_{i}\neq 0$ (otherwise, it is equal to 1). When $n=0$ and/or $m=0$, there is only one 1-morphism $n\longrightarrow m$, which will be denoted by ${\bf 0}_{n,m}$. • 2-morphism: given objects $n,m\geq 1$ and 1-morphisms $({\bf R},s),({\bf R}^{\prime},s^{\prime}):n\longrightarrow m$, with ${\bf R}=(R_{ij})_{i=1,\ldots,m,j=1,\ldots,n}$ and ${\bf R}^{\prime}=(R^{\prime}_{ij})_{i=1,\ldots,m,j=1,\ldots,n}$, a 2-morphism $({\bf R},s)\Rightarrow({\bf R}^{\prime},s^{\prime})$ is an $m\times n$ matrix T whose $(i,j)$ entry ${\sf T}_{ij}$ is an $R^{\prime}_{ij}\times R_{ij}$ complex matrix if both $R_{ij},R^{\prime}_{ij}\neq 0$ and empty otherwise. If $n=0$ and/or $m=0$, both 1-morphisms are necessarily equal and there is a unique 2-morphism between them denoted $1_{{\bf 0}_{n,m}}$ (obviously, it is the identity 2-morphism of ${\bf 0}_{n,m}$). The various compositions are as follows: • composition of 1-morphisms: if $n,m,p\geq 1$ and $({\bf R},s):n\longrightarrow m$ and $(\widetilde{{\bf R}},\widetilde{s}):m\longrightarrow p$, the composite $(\widetilde{{\bf R}},\widetilde{s})\circ({\bf R},s):n\longrightarrow p$ is the pair $(\widetilde{{\bf R}},\widetilde{s})\circ({\bf R},s)=(\widetilde{{\bf R}}{\bf R% },\widetilde{s}\ast s)$ where $\widetilde{{\bf R}}{\bf R}$ denotes the usual matrix product and $\widetilde{s}\ast s$ is defined by $\displaystyle(\widetilde{s}\ast s)_{k}({\bf a})=\widetilde{s}_{k}({\bf R}({\bf a% }))$ $\displaystyle\left(\bigoplus_{i=1}^{m}Id_{\widetilde{R}_{ki}}\otimes s_{i}({% \bf a})\right){\bf P}(\widetilde{{\bf R}}_{k},{\bf R},{\bf a})$ $\displaystyle \left(\bigoplus_{j=1}^{n}\ \widetilde{s}_{k}({\bf R}(% {\bf e}_{j}))^{-1}\otimes Id_{a_{j}}\right)$ for all ${\bf a}\in\mathbb{N}^{n}$ and $k=1,\ldots,p$ ($Id_{0}$ means the empty matrix). Here, ${\bf P}(\widetilde{{\bf R}}_{k},{\bf R},{\bf a})$ denote the permutation matrices of order $\sum_{j=1}^{n}\sum_{i=1}^{m}\widetilde{R}_{ki}R_{ij}a_{j}$ introduced in Definition 3.7 and satisfying the normalization conditions in Lemma 3.8. In case one of the numbers $n,m,p$ is zero, the composite is the corresponding zero map. • vertical composition of 2-morphisms: given 2-morphisms ${\sf T}:({\bf R},s)\Rightarrow({\bf R}^{\prime},s^{\prime})$ and ${\sf T}^{\prime}:({\bf R}^{\prime},s^{\prime})\Rightarrow({\bf R}^{\prime% \prime},s^{\prime\prime})$, with $({\bf R},s),({\bf R}^{\prime},s^{\prime}),({\bf R}^{\prime\prime},s^{\prime% \prime}):n\longrightarrow m$ and $n,m\geq 1$, the vertical composite ${\sf T}^{\prime}\cdot{\sf T}:({\bf R},s)\Rightarrow({\bf R}^{\prime\prime},s^{% \prime\prime})$ is the matrix obtained by componentwise multiplication, i.e. $({\sf T}^{\prime}\cdot{\sf T})_{ij}={\sf T}^{\prime}_{ij}{\sf T}_{ij},\quad i=% 1,\ldots,m,\ j=1,\ldots,n$ where we agree that the product of a matrix by the empty matrix is the empty matrix or the appropriate zero matrix (for example, if $R^{\prime}_{ij}=0$ but $R_{ij},R^{\prime\prime}_{ij}\neq 0$, we have ${\sf T}_{ij}={\sf T}^{\prime}_{ij}=\emptyset$, while $({\sf T}^{\prime}\cdot{\sf T})_{ij}$ is the $R^{\prime\prime}_{ij}\times R_{ij}$ zero matrix). • horizontal composition of 2-morphisms: given 2-morphisms ${\sf T}:({\bf R},s)\Rightarrow({\bf R}^{\prime},s^{\prime}):n\longrightarrow m$ and $\widetilde{{\sf T}}:(\widetilde{{\bf R}},\widetilde{s})\Rightarrow(\widetilde{% {\bf R}}^{\prime},\widetilde{s}^{\prime}):m\longrightarrow p$, with $n,m,p\geq 1$, the horizontal composite $\widetilde{{\sf T}}\circ{\sf T}$ is the $p\times n$ matrix with entries defined by $(\widetilde{{\sf T}}\circ{\sf T})_{kj}=\widetilde{s}^{\prime}_{k}({\bf R}^{% \prime}({\bf e}_{j}))\left(\bigoplus_{i=1}^{m}\ \widetilde{{\sf T}}_{ki}% \otimes{\sf T}_{ij}\right)\widetilde{s}_{k}({\bf R}({\bf e}_{j}))^{-1}$ for all $j=1,\ldots,n$ and $k=1,\ldots,p$, where we agree again that the tensor product of any matrix by the empty matrix is the empty matrix.
Definition 3.7 In the above notations, we denote by ${\bf P}({\bf R}^{\prime}_{k},{\bf R},{\bf a})$ the matrix defined as follows: (i) ${\bf P}({\bf R}^{\prime}_{k},{\bf R},(1,\stackrel{{\scriptstyle n)}}{{\ldots}}% ,1))$ is the unique permutation matrix involving no change in the order of the various copies of $[f_{j}]$, for each $j=1,\ldots,n$, when going from $[H(\widetilde{{\bf R}}_{k})(f_{1},\ldots,f_{n})]$ to (3.20) (see example above), and (ii) ${\bf P}({\bf R}^{\prime}_{k},{\bf R},{\bf a})$, for ${\bf a}\neq(1,\stackrel{{\scriptstyle n)}}{{\ldots}},1)$, is that obtained from ${\bf P}({\bf R}^{\prime}_{k},{\bf R},(1,\stackrel{{\scriptstyle n)}}{{\ldots}}% ,1))$ by replacing each nonzero entry by an identity or an empty matrix, according to the value of the corresponding $a_{j}$, and simultaneously deleting the zero entries or replacing them by suitable zero matrices so that the resulting matrix becomes a square matrix of dimension $\sum_{j=1}^{n}\sum_{i=1}^{m}{\bf R}^{\prime}_{ki}{\bf R}_{ij}a_{j}$.
Definition 2.1 Let 2SVect be the 2-category whose objects, 1-morphisms and 2-morphisms are respectively the $\mathbb{C}$-linear additive categories ${\bf{SVect}}^{n}$ for all $n\geq 0$, the $\mathbb{C}$-linear (hence, additive) functors $F:{\bf{SVect}}^{n}\longrightarrow{\bf{SVect}}^{m}$ and the natural transformations, with the usual compositions of functors and natural transformations and usual 1- and 2-identities.
Definition 3.4 The $m$-tuple of normalized sections $(s_{1},\ldots,s_{m})\in\mathcal{S}({\bf R}_{1})\times\cdots\times\mathcal{S}({% \bf R}_{m})$ defining a functor $F:{\bf{SVect}}^{n}\longrightarrow{\bf{SVect}}^{m}$ with rank matrix ${\bf R}$ will be called the gauge of the functor (with respect to the above chosen references $\{H({\bf r})\}_{{\bf r}}$).
Definition 3.1 (The geometric nerve). Consider the full and faithful functor ${\text{\bf i}}:{{\Delta}}\to{2\text{-}{\sf Cat}_{\text{\rm lax}}}$ defined by regarding each simplex $[n]$ as a 2-category whose only deformations are the required identities (this forces all lax 2-functors $[n]\to[m]$ to be just functors or monotonic maps). Using this embedding as in (3) one gets a nerve functor ${\text{\sf Ner}}:{2\text{-}{\sf Cat}_{\text{\rm lax}}}\to{{\sf Sset}}$ such that for any 2-category ${\mathbf{A}}$, ${\text{\sf Ner}}({\mathbf{A}})$ is the simplicial set ${\text{\sf Ner}}({\mathbf{A}})={\text{\sf LaxFun}}\big{(}{\text{\bf i}}(-),{% \mathbf{A}}\big{)},\qquad\vbox{\xymatrix@C=4mm{ {{{\Delta}}^{\text{\rm op}}}% \ar[rr]^{{\text{\sf Ner}}({\mathbf{A}})} \ar[dr]_{{{\text{\bf i}}^{\text{\rm op% }}}} & & {{\sf Set}}\\ & {{2\text{-}{\sf Cat}_{\text{\rm lax}}}^{\text{\rm op}}}\ar[ur]_{{\text{\sf LaxFun% }}(-,{\mathbf{A}})} }}$
Definition 5.6. For a map $f\in\mathscr{M}^{C},$ we will refer to the maps $f(\alpha)\colon X(\alpha)\rightarrow Y(\alpha)$ where $\alpha\in C$ as component maps (specifically the component map of $f$ at $\alpha$).
Definition 3.9. [16, 1.0] Let $C$ be a pointed closed simplicial model category and $A$ be a cofibrant object of $C.$ We call $C^{A}$ a closed model category structure associated with the localization of $C$ with respect to $A$ if the cofibrations, fibrations and weak equivalences in $C^{A}$ are defined as follows: • $W_{C^{A}}\mathrel{\mathop{:}}=\{\varphi\colon B\rightarrow C|\varphi_{f_{\ast}% }\colon\Hom(A,\tilde{B})\rightarrow\Hom(A,C)$ is a weak equivalence of simplicial sets $\}$ • $Fib_{C^{A}}\mathrel{\mathop{:}}=Fib_{C}$ • $Cof_{C^{A}}\mathrel{\mathop{:}}=\mathop{}\mathopen{\vphantom{(W_{C^{A}}\cap Fib% _{C^{A}})}}^{\cancel{\square}}\kern-0.5pt(W_{C^{A}}\cap Fib_{C^{A}})$ where $\varphi_{f_{\ast}}$ is the fibrant approximation of $\varphi.$
Definition 2.2. A model category structure on a category $\mathscr{M}$ consists of three classes of maps $\mathscr{F},\mathscr{C}$ and $\mathscr{W}$ called fibrations, cofibrations and weak equivalences respectively so that $\mathscr{W}$ satisfies the 2 out of 3 property, and $(\mathscr{C}\cap\mathscr{W},\mathscr{F})$ and $(\mathscr{C},\mathscr{F}\cap\mathscr{W})$ are weak factorization systems.
Definition 3.1. Given a category $\mathscr{M}$ with a model category structure which we denote $\mathscr{M}_{1}$ a right Bousfield localization of $\mathscr{M}$ is an additional model category structure on $\mathscr{M}$ (denoted $\mathscr{M}_{2}$) with the following properties: • if $f$ is a weak equivalence in the $\mathscr{M}_{1}$ model category structure, then $f$ is a weak equivalence in the $\mathscr{M}_{2}$ model category structure • $\mathscr{M}_{1}$ and $\mathscr{M}_{2}$ have the same class of fibrations.
Definition 5.2. Let $\mathscr{M}$ be a category and $C$ be a small category. By $\mathscr{M}^{C}$ we mean the category of diagrams in $\mathscr{M}$ with the shape of $C.$ Objects in $\mathscr{M}^{C}$ are functors from $C$ to $\mathscr{M}$ and morphisms are natural transformations.
Definition 2.1. [18, 2] A weak factorization system $(L,R)$ on a category $\mathscr{M}$ consists of two classes of maps so that • Any map $f\in\mathscr{M}$ can be factored as $f=r\circ l$ with $l\in L$ and $r\in R.$ • Any lifting problem, i.e., any commutative diagram of the form has a solution, i.e., a diagonal arrow making both triangles commute. • The classes $L$ and $R$ are closed under retracts.
Definition 2.6. [13, 3.3.1] Let $\mathscr{M}$ be a model category and $S$ be a class of maps in $\mathscr{M}.$ (1) The left Bousfield localization of $\mathscr{M}$ with respect to $S$ (if it exists) is a model category structure $L_{S}\mathscr{M}$ on the underlying category $\mathscr{M}$ such that a) the class of weak equivalences of $L_{S}\mathscr{M}$ equals the class of $S$-local equivalences of $\mathscr{M}$ b) the class of cofibrations of $L_{S}\mathscr{M}$ equals the class of cofibrations of $\mathscr{M}$ and c) the class of fibrations of $L_{S}\mathscr{M}$ is the class of maps with the right lifting property with respect to maps which are both $S$-local equivalences and cofibrations. (2) The right Bousfield localization of $\mathscr{M}$ with respect to $S$ (if it exists) is a model category structure $R_{S}\mathscr{M}$ on the underlying category $\mathscr{M}$ such that a) the class of weak equivalences of $R_{S}\mathscr{M}$ equals the class of $S$-colocal equivalences of $\mathscr{M}$ b) the class of fibrations of $R_{S}\mathscr{M}$ equals the class of fibrations of $\mathscr{M}$ and c) the class of cofibrations of $R_{S}\mathscr{M}$ is the class of maps with the left lifting property with respect to maps which are both $S$-colocal equivalences and fibrations.
